annotation.TEXT: Final casting for the role of Rob Petrie came down to two actors: Dick Van Dyke (who ultimately got the part) and Johnny Carson.
Thirsty Thursday, as celebrated in many bars and restaurants, originated on college campuses, where students often began their weekends early.
A play on the phrase “Hail, friend, and well met.” A variation, “hail-fellow-well-met,” is an adjective meaning friendly, congenial, and hearty.
Monday Night Football used this Hank Williams Jr. song as its theme from 1989 until 2011, when Williams compared then-President Barack Obama to Hitler.
This presentation was brought to you by the Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Mel Tormé, aka the “Velvet Fog,” was one of the 20th century’s most respected jazz vocalists, with a smooth, resonant voice.
Deep Purple is a British hard rock band that scored its biggest hit with 1972’s “Smoke on the Water.”
The original logo for the Olive Garden chain of Italian restaurants included a bunch of grapes with a trailing grapevine. It was changed in 2014.
French author Marcel Proust is best known for his 7-volume allegorical autobiography À la recherche du temps perdu (Remembrance of Things Past).
Friar Tuck was the priest in the Robin Hood legend, although he (along with Maid Marian) was a relatively late addition to the stories.
Topol is a singer and actor best known for playing family patriarch Tevye in the musical Fiddler on the Roof.
In 1993, NBC began using the phrase “Must See TV” for their dominant Thursday-night comedy lineup; they finally retired the slogan in 2015.
The Knights of Columbus is a fraternal order for Catholic men that was originally founded in 1882 to provide support to needy members’ families.
The Denver boot is a thingamabob used by police to immobilize the cars of drivers with unpaid parking tickets, etc. It was first used by the Denver PD in 1955.
Chiang Kai-shek was deposed as leader of China by Mao Zedong’s Communist forces in 1949; he fled to the island of Taiwan, where he led the Chinese government-in-exile until his death.
“Light and get away” is a common warning on fireworks.
Grumpy and Sneezy were two of the seven dwarfs in the Walt Disney animated film Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs. The others were Dopey, Sleepy, Happy, Bashful, and Doc.
Oregon Senator Bob Packwood resigned in 1995 after a series of explosive sexual harassment charges, ranging from kissing to forceful groping.
In 2001, Homer Simpson’s iconic “D’oh!” made it into the Oxford English Dictionary, thus becoming enshrined in the English language.
TV announcer Dennis James appeared in ads for Physicians Mutual Insurance Co. for 30 years.
Ray Price was a country artist who made it big in 1956 with the #1 hit “Crazy Arms.”
Founding father Patrick Henry delivered these words in 1775 in a speech to the second Virginia Convention.
An ice auger is a tool used to drill a hole through the ice over a body of water for ice fishing.
Ray Nitschke was a feared yet beloved linebacker for the Green Bay Packers from 1958-72. He was known for being ruthless on the field but a caring, generous family man off it.
An imitation of a traditional cheerleading chant.
A line from the Eagles song “Take It Easy.”
A yarmulke is a type of kippah, the small round cap worn by many Jews during religious ceremonies; some conservative Jews wear it every day.
In the song “Tevye’s Dream,” from the musical Fiddler on the Roof, Tevye tells his wife of a terrible dream in which a ghost named Fruma-Sarah threatened their daughter.
A line from a 1981 song by Don Henley and Stevie Nicks, “Leather and Lace.”
On the ‘70s cop show Starsky & Hutch, Huggy Bear (played by Antonio Fargas) was the flamboyantly dressed pimp who was a reliable source of “word on the street” information for the police.
Driving Miss Daisy is a film starring Jessica Tandy as a cantankerous old woman and Morgan Freeman as her chauffeur.
In 1986, the Motel 6 chain began airing a series of ads with Tom Bodett that used the tagline “We’ll leave the light on for you.” The famous line was ad-libbed.
Loden is a thick, waterproof, woolen fabric, as well as the name of the dark green color that loden garments are often dyed.
Satan (aka the devil) is the personification of evil in Christian and Islamic traditions, though his initial job seems to have been as a prosecutor of sorts, sent to test men’s faith.
Actor Billy Barty was 3’9”; he also played the hapless bookseller in Foul Play and Sigmund in Sigmund and the Sea Monsters.
Dogs do go through the same sleep stages as humans, and animal experts believe they also dream—hence the twitching—but the content of those dreams is unknown.
Did we miss any references? Let us know in the comments!
An imitation of Mel Cooley (played by Richard Deacon) on The Dick Van Dyke Show. Rob Petrie (Dick Van Dyke) was the lead character on the show, and Alan Brady (Carl Reiner) was their boss.
Sir John Falstaff, a fat, drunken but witty knight, appears in 4 plays by Shakespeare. The Merry Wives of Windsor was supposedly written for Queen Elizabeth I, who wanted to see Falstaff in love.
San Juan Capistrano is a Catholic mission in SoCal famous for its annual “return of the swallows,” which supposedly return on March 19 (St. Joseph’s Day).
The balding, nearsighted Neil Simon is an American playwright known for his lightweight, audience-pleasing comedies.
The annual MDA Labor Day Telethon was a 21-hour event hosted by comedian Jerry Lewis from 1966-2010. In 2015 MDA dropped the telethon altogether.
A skort is a cross between a skirt and a pair of shorts that were popular in the ‘90s.
Mylar is an extremely strong polyester film developed by DuPont in the ‘50s.
A paraphrase of John Cleese’s line from the “Encyclopedia Salesman” skit on Monty Python’s Flying Circus.
Wings is a ‘90s TV sitcom that starred Tim Daly and Steven Weber as two bickering brothers who run an air charter service in Nantucket.
A riff on Groucho Marx’s signature song “Lydia the Tattooed Lady,” which first appeared in the 1939 Marx Brothers film At the Circus.
Michael Eisner was the chairman and CEO of Walt Disney Productions for 21 years. For decades he was one of the richest and most powerful men in Hollywood.
Ozzy Osbourne was the front man for the heavy metal band Black Sabbath. He later had a successful solo career and in the early 2000s became a reality TV star.
A reference to the traditional Christmas carol “The Little Drummer Boy,” written in 1941 by Katherine Kennicott Davis.
The fast-food chain Burger King has traditionally handed out gold paper crowns to children at their hosted birthday parties.
An imitation of Darrin Stephens on the TV show Bewitched. Possibly a reference to the episode “The Cat’s Meow,” in which Darrin thinks his wife Sam has turned herself into a cat.
The Lollipop Guild is the group of Munchkins who welcome Dorothy to Oz in The Wizard of Oz.
The green Peter Pan elf hat did not become indelibly associated with the character until the Disney film came out in 1953.
The zipper didn’t debut until the 1893 Chicago World’s Fair, while the first commercially available zipper came in 1913.
Plague and the Black Death are often considered synonymous, but the same bacteria that causes bubonic plague can also cause septicemic and pneumonic plague.
Embers is a chain of family-style restaurants with locations throughout the upper Midwest. It is based in St. Paul, MN.
Geek-rock/new-wave band Devo’s first album, released in 1978, was titled Q: Are We Not Men? A: We Are Devo!
‘80s British ska group Madness was best known in the US for their hit single “Our House.” Squeeze was another UK ‘80s ska band; their song “Tempted” has been used in several ads.
Recombining DNA is the process by which genes from two different organisms are combined to create a hybrid. It is commonly used by scientists studying heredity.
Leather mugs (usually made waterproof with beeswax or resin or with a plastic insert) are sold at Renaissance festivals, which sprouted in SoCal in the ‘60s.
An imitation of Johnny the hand puppet.
It was driven home by Bela Lugosi’s character in MST3K Episode 423, Bride of the Monster.
A line from the song “The Windmills of Your Mind” by Dusty Springfield.
The catchphrase of diminutive actor Gary Coleman on the early ‘80s TV series Diff’rent Strokes.
A reference to the 1990 song “I Touch Myself” by the Divinyls.
Decoupage is a decorative folk art in which an object is covered with small pieces of paper or gold leaf and then covered with multiple layers of varnish.
In an infamous outtake from the film Apocalypse Now, while solemnly declaiming one of his big speeches, Marlon Brando stops, grimaces horribly, and says, “I swallowed a bug.”
A paraphrase of the traditional Christmas carol “God Rest Ye Merry, Gentlemen,” which dates at least to the 16th century.
Meat Loaf (b. Marvin Lee Aday) is a famously beefy musician who peaked in the ‘70s, with such hits as “Bat Out of Hell” and “Paradise by the Dashboard Light.”
A long-line bra extends down to the wearer’s waist and acts as a girdle to restrain unsightly fat.
Nancy Walker appeared in a long-running series of ads for Bounty paper towels (the “quicker-picker-upper”). She also played Ida Morgenstern on The Mary Tyler Moore Show and Rhoda.
A 1987 ad for the US Marines Corps featured an armored knight who transformed into a modern Marine in dress uniform.
This is apparently from an old TV ad campaign trying to attract tourists to Ontario, Canada.
Another possible inspiration: frequent early ‘80s talk show guest and “World’s Fastest Hypnotist” Marshall Syler would entrance people while barking “Sleep!” at them.
The tagline for the 1976 Roger Corman film Eat My Dust was “Ron Howard pops the clutch and tells the world: Eat My Dust!”
John McLaughlin was the host of The McLaughlin Group, a political affairs discussion show on PBS, from 1982 until his death in 2016.
Georges Feydeau was a French playwright around the turn of the 20th century who specialized in witty, complex farces. They are still performed today.
The close-cropped Dwight D. Eisenhower was the supreme commander of the Allied forces in Europe during WWII and later president of the US during the ‘50s.
The theme to the ‘60s TV sitcom The Dick Van Dyke Show. The show’s credits began with Van Dyke opening the door to his house and walking in.
A line from the 1978 song “Who Are You” by The Who.
Chili’s Grill & Bar is a chain of “family restaurants” that aired endless ads in the ‘80s & ‘90s touting its “baby-back ribs.”
The earliest known print version of the nursery rhyme “Little Miss Muffet” appeared in 1805, although some attribute it to Thomas Muffet, an entomologist who died in 1604.
Tucks Medicated Pads are used to relieve the symptoms of hemorrhoids.
Smokey the Bear is the longtime spokescreature for the U.S. Forest Service. His slogan from 1947-2001: “Only you can prevent forest fires.”
The Night of the Iguana is a Tennessee Williams play about an ex-minister working as a tour guide in Mexico. It was made into a film starring Richard Burton in 1964.
Now please enjoy…the fully annotated The Undead!
An imitation of the “Tomahawk Chop,” used first by fans of the Florida State Seminoles in the ‘80s and then by Atlanta Braves fans in the ‘90s.
Dance belts aren’t actually belts. They’re support garments for the genitals.
The Central Time Zone covers such states as Minnesota, Illinois, Missouri, Oklahoma, and Texas.
In the original 1977 Star Wars, Princess Leia (Carrie Fisher) famously hides a recording on R2-D2 that says in part, “Help me, Obi-Wan Kenobi. You’re my only hope.”
Now you can learn the truth behind all the references.
Early in the 1990 film Ghost, there is a famous scene where Demi Moore and Patrick Swayze have a makeout session over a pottery wheel.
A line from the 1979 song “We Are Family” by Sister Sledge.
An infamous, often-used riff that conflates two misremembered ads for Grape-Nuts and Ivory Soap in the ‘70s.
An imitation of a baseball announcer. The warning track is the strip of dirt that runs around the outside of the field, “warning” players they are about to slam into the fence.
Mordor is the blighted land ruled by the evil Sauron in The Lord of the Rings.
A paraphrase of the 1974 song “Sundown” by Gordon Lightfoot.
Dangerous Liaisons is a film about the lives and loves of the corrupt French aristocracy in the years before the French Revolution. It is based on the novel Les Liaisons dangereuses.
The TV show The Fugitive starred David Janssen as a man unjustly convicted of murder and fleeing the cops while hunting down the real killer—the mysterious “one-armed man.”
Ben Franklin actually did say this one, although he swiped it from John Clarke, who published it in 1639.
The Alpine Valley Music Theatre is a concert venue in East Troy, WI; the Grateful Dead performed there many times.
King Koil is a brand of mattress, originally made by a company in St. Paul, MN.
In J.R.R. Tolkien’s The Lord of the Rings, the hobbit Frodo wears a mithril vest that can withstand spears and swords.
And let us know if we missed any references!
Andrew “Squiggy” Squiggman (David L. Lander) was one of the wacky neighbors on the sitcom Laverne & Shirley.
TV drama Adam-12 was one of the first cop shows to use realistic police procedures and jargon, and patrol car chatter was often used for exposition.
The limbo is a dance originating in Trinidad in which the dancer bends backwards to walk under a bar that is made progressively lower as the dance goes on.
Fluffernutter, popular among kids as a sandwich spread, is a combination of peanut butter and marshmallow fluff.
Hardware Hank is a chain of retail hardware stores in the US. It is based in Minnesota.
A paraphrase of Rhett Butler’s famous line at the end of the film Gone with the Wind: “Frankly, my dear, I don’t give a damn.”
Señor Wences was a Spanish ventriloquist who often appeared on The Ed Sullivan Show. He was known for his comic banter with a hand puppet named Johnny.
A reference to a Groucho Marx line in the Marx Brothers movie Animal Crackers, which itself is a reference to the experimental Eugene O'Neill play Strange Interlude.
A version of “Three Blind Mice” was published as early as 1609, although with somewhat different lyrics. “Hickory Dickory Dock” dates to 1744.
Weekend at Bernie’s is a film about two young men who decide to pretend their murdered boss is still alive. Tasteless hijinks ensue.

Pyramid schemes are a classic scam in which people are recruited to sell something; however, the real purpose is to recruit others, who will pay a “commission” to the people above them in the pyramid.
Big Wheels are a brand of tricycle that boast a much larger front wheel than the two back wheels. Introduced in 1969, they were highly popular in the ‘70s.
The B-1 bomber, introduced to the U.S. armed forces in 1986, was a strategic bomber designed to evade enemy radar by flying at low levels.
Des Moines is the capital city of Iowa, with a population of roughly 623,000, none of whom appear to be shamans.
Tudor houses are characterized by the half-timbered style (where the beams of the house are still visible) and long, sloping roofs.
Benjamin Franklin was a printer, author, diplomat, inventor, and scientist who was one of the U.S. founding fathers.
“Nights in White Satin” is a 1967 song by the Moody Blues.
In 1955, Carmen Miranda had a heart attack and fell during a dance number on Jimmy Durante’s TV show, and Durante shouted, “Stop da music!” Sadly, she died the next day.
And The Undead comes to a close.
Phil Harris played himself on radio’s The Jack Benny Program and later had his own long-running radio show. He also voiced Baloo the Bear and Little John for Disney.
Backdraft is a film directed by Ron Howard about two firefighter brothers in Chicago who face a deadly arsonist.
Waldo Weatherbee is the principal of Riverdale High School in the Archie comic books, created by John Goldwater. He first appeared in 1942.
“Huzzah” is an olde English exclamation, similar to “hurray,” that has been around since Shakespeare’s time.
Hooters is a chain of restaurants whose attractive waitresses all dress in tight tank tops and very short shorts. Its corporate symbol is an owl.
“SLEEP!” first appeared in MST3K Episode 302, Gamera.
Fancy Feast was introduced in 1982 as the first “gourmet” cat food, in ads with a finicky Persian cat dining from a glass goblet.
The 1996 film version of the Arthur Miller play The Crucible starred Winona Ryder as a jealous woman in Salem, MA, who accuses her ex-lover’s wife of being a witch.
Mad magazine was first published in 1952 as a comic book from EC Comics; it is now the last surviving publication from that legendary company.
Tom Glavine was a pitcher for the Atlanta Braves and the NY Mets; he played from 1987-2010.
A paraphrase of the song “The Devil Went Down to Georgia,” which was a hit for The Charlie Daniels Band in 1979, and again when it was used in the 1980 film Urban Cowboy.
A parody of the Grammy Award-winning Allan Sherman song “Hello Muddah, Hello Fadduh.”
“Graveyard smash” and “Transylvania twist” are lyrics from the 1962 novelty hit “Monster Mash” by Bobby “Boris” Pickett and the Crypt-Kickers.
This was three-time NYC mayor Ed Koch’s well-known catchphrase.
A typical opening for one of Penthouse’s letters.
The Ranger Strider, aka Aragorn, is one of the central characters in J.R.R. Tolkien’s The Lord of the Rings.
“Bewitched, Bothered and Bewildered” is a song from the Rodgers and Hart musical Pal Joey. It has become a standard, recorded by innumerable artists.
Route 66, or the Mother Road, was built in 1926 as one of the first major interstate highways, running from Chicago to LA.
Kaye Ballard was known for musical comedy in the ‘50s and ‘60s, working with Spike Jones and playing one of the wicked stepsisters opposite Julie Andrews in Cinderella.
From 1 Corinthians 13:12: “For now we see through a glass, darkly.” Ingrid Bergman used it as the title of his 1961 film about a young woman suffering from mental illness.
Peter Pan, “the boy who wouldn’t grow up,” was based on author J.M. Barrie’s older brother, who died in an accident at the age of 13.
Entrepreneur and inventor David Dunbar Buick produced the first Buick car in 1899.
An imitation of Margaret Hamilton as the Wicked Witch in The Wizard of Oz.
The 1939 film The Wizard of Oz featured Frank Morgan as a medicine man named Professor Marvel, peddling his wares from a cart; in Oz, he is transformed into the Wizard.
Reginald Jeeves was the imperturbable valet in the farcical Jeeves and Wooster novels by P.G. Wodehouse. He was named after a pro cricketer killed in WWI.
Thomas Jefferson was the founding father who had a scandalous affair with his slave Sally Hemings; Ben Franklin, while not averse to the ladies, freed his two male slaves.
The mid-‘80s saw a barrage of media coverage about a new method of getting high: licking cane toads, which supposedly secreted a hallucinogenic substance.
In Joel Hodgson’s days as a prop comic, fellow comic Gallagher was rude and dismissive to him backstage, leading to years of insulting riffs on MST3K.
Mad About You was a ‘90s TV sitcom starring Paul Reiser and Helen Hunt as NYC newlyweds.
Radon is a carcinogenic gas that causes about 21,000 deaths a year in the US from lung cancer. It was discovered as a health hazard in the mid-‘80s.
Did we miss any? Let us know in the comments.
Frangelico is a hazelnut-flavored liqueur that according to legend was developed by Italian monks about 300 years ago. Its bottle shape suggests a monk with folded arms.
A paraphrase of Gloria Swanson’s famous line from the film Sunset Boulevard: “All right, Mr. DeMille, I’m ready for my close-up.”
Malibu is a SoCal hillside community that has faced repeated wildfires since its founding. The 1956 fire killed one person and burned 120 homes.
Smoked turkey legs, popular at street fairs and Renaissance festivals, weigh in at an impressive 1,400 calories and 68 grams of fat apiece.
Actor Mike Farrell is best known for playing surgeon B.J. Hunnicutt on the TV series M*A*S*H.
Beefalo are a cross between bison and cattle, resulting in a meat that is lower in fat and cholesterol while still tasting like beef.
A reference to MST3K Episode 521, Santa Claus.
An imitation of the audience on the long-running TV game show Let’s Make a Deal.
In the Coen Brothers movie Fargo, a quarrel between kidnappers results in one of them killing the other and disposing of the body with a wood chipper.
The debonair Noel Coward was a British playwright who specialized in plays featuring upper-class Brits standing around in country houses trading quips.
An imitation of Ray Szmanda, the hyper-exuberant man who appeared in roughly 6,000 ads during his 20-plus-year career as the pitchman for home-improvement chain Menards.
James Coco was a portly actor who got his start on Broadway and went on to countless small character roles in movies and TV.
Some of these noises resemble those of The Three Stooges, particularly the “whinnying” of Shemp Howard (b. Samuel Horwitz).
Quentin Crisp was a British writer, actor, and gay icon. Sting wrote the song “Englishman in New York” after meeting Crisp.
In the Bible, Beelzebub is referred to as the prince of demons, but it is also the name of the god worshiped by the Philistine city Ekron.
Tin Pan Alley was a popular genre of music in the early 20th century, taking its name from the NYC street that was the center of the music publishing business.
Ziploc is a brand of plastic storage bags. A meat diaper is the colloquial name for the cellulose liner that comes in foam meat trays to absorb the juices; its official name is a meat pad.
Winn-Dixie is a chain of grocery stores in the South. The second part of the riff is from the Shakespeare play Macbeth, part of the three witches’ spell.
A reference to MST3K Episode 310, Fugitive Alien.
The Lincoln Park Zoo is in Chicago. Founded in 1868, it boasts an impressive great ape exhibit and is renowned for its gorilla breeding program.
A reference to the rhyming, politically incorrect, and insulting term for a woman who hangs around with a male homosexual.
Actress Margaret Hamilton was best known for playing the Wicked Witch of the West in the film The Wizard of Oz.
Actor James Woods is known for playing quirky, occasionally psychotic roles. He has appeared in such films as The Onion Field and Videodrome.
A reference to the 1989 song “If I Could Turn Back Time” by Cher.
An imitation of Col. Wilhelm Klink (Werner Klemperer) in Hogan’s Heroes, a ‘60s sitcom about a Nazi POW camp.
ZZ Top is a blues-rock band from Houston, known as much for their lush, majestic beards as for their songs, which include “Sharp Dressed Man” and “Legs.”
A parody of the 1979 song “We Are Family” by Sister Sledge.
A Gabriel’s horn is a mathematical construct that has infinite surface area, but finite volume.
One theory on the origin of golf course sand traps holds that they evolved from sheep bedding down behind sand dunes near early courses, which dug out natural hollows over time.
The disembodied voice of the computer in most of the Star Trek TV shows and films was played by Majel Barrett, who also played Nurse Christine Chapel on the original show.
A variation on the standard magician’s line “There’s nothing up my sleeve.” A jerkin is a 16th- and 17th-century men’s jacket, usually sleeveless and made of leather.
Quest for Fire is a film about three prehistoric men searching for a source of fire to replace the flame their tribe has lost.
In one scene in the film Flashdance, star Jennifer Beals wore an oversized sweatshirt with the collar cut off so it would slip off one shoulder; it created a brief but widespread fashion fad.
Actor John Goodman’s first professional work was in voiceovers and ads in the ‘70s. His first film role was a small part in 1983’s Eddie Macon’s Run.
A shortened form of “brewtowski,” one of the myriad slang terms for beer.
A running gag from the Steve Martin movie The Man With Two Brains.
A variant on a drinking toast dating back to the ‘30s. Another version: “Look out, liver, here it comes!”
A line from The Addams Family TV series and films: whenever Morticia spoke French, it would drive Gomez into an amorous frenzy. Kissing would be involved.
With annotations provided by The Annotated MST website.
The original Nimrod was a mighty hunter and the great-great-grandson of Noah. In US slang it means a hopeless dweeb, thanks to Bugs Bunny, who used it as a nickname for Elmer Fudd.
An imitation of Curly Howard (b. Jerome Lester Horwitz) of the Three Stooges, a comedy trio that appeared in nearly 200 short films.
Phil Spector is a music producer who created the famous Wall of Sound. In 2009 he was convicted of murdering actress Lana Clarkson.
Jan Murray was an actor and comedian of the borscht belt variety who performed his standup act in the Catskills and in Las Vegas.
Warriors of the Wasteland is an Italian film about post-apocalyptic mercenaries fighting off evil bikers. It is also the title of a 1986 song by the band Frankie Goes to Hollywood.
In J.R.R. Tolkien’s classic fantasy trilogy The Lord of the Rings, Rivendell is one of the last remaining homes of Elves in Middle Earth. It is ruled by the Elf lord Elrond.
June Taylor was a TV choreographer from the ‘40s-‘60s. Her “June Taylor dancers” were a regular feature on the old Jackie Gleason Show.
In 1997, actor Anthony Quinn married his longtime secretary Kathy Benvin, making her his third wife. He was 82; she was 35.
Muncie, Indiana, is a city about 50 miles northeast of Indianapolis. It was originally settled by the Lenape tribe, which called it Munsee Town.
Tote bags are standard swag offered during the lengthy and tiresome pledge drives frequently held by PBS and NPR stations.
Leinenkugel beers, nicknamed “Leinies,” are produced by the Jacob Leinenkugel Brewing Co. of Chippewa Falls, WI.
The origin of the popular dessert name “Death by Chocolate” is obscure, but many attribute it to chef Marcel Desaulniers, who published a 1992 cookbook under that title.
Leo Sayer is a British musician who had a string of mainstream pop hits, such as “When I Need You,” in the ‘70s.
Smudging is a mostly outdated practice of protecting citrus crops from frost by lighting “smudge pots,” oil burners set throughout the orchards to keep the trees warm.
Actress Kitty Carlisle was a regular panelist on the TV game show To Tell the Truth; on that show, celebrities tried to figure out which contestant was telling the truth about their life story.
Bill Diehl was the longtime film critic for the St. Paul Pioneer Press-Dispatch; he was also a well-known local DJ and talent agent. He retired in 1996.
“A penny saved is a penny earned” is attributed to Ben Franklin, but it was actually penned in 1661 by Thomas Fuller.
Rice Dream is a milk substitute made from rice.
A line from the “Spanish Inquisition” sketch from the classic BBC series Monty Python’s Flying Circus.
David Brinkley was a TV journalist who hosted the news show This Week with David Brinkley for 15 years. He was known for his clipped delivery and sardonic wit.
An expression from basketball, “nothing but net” means to make a basket so precisely that the ball only touches the net as it goes through, not the backboard or rim.
Choreographer/director Bob Fosse was behind some of the all-time classic musicals of the 20th century, including Damn Yankees, Cabaret, and Chicago.
The Undead: Fully annotated by The Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
666 is traditionally regarded by Christians as “the number of the beast,” or a mark that identifies the Antichrist, a belief that comes from Revelation.
Let’s take a moment to recognize the fact that Roger Corman directed or produced 7 films riffed on by MST3K, second only to Bert I. Gordon’s 8 films.
Dwarf tossing is a pub sport in England and its former colonies in which contestants compete to see how far they can throw a dwarf.
